@NODE INTRO "Introduction"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Introduction@{ub}


SimpleFind3 is a Search-Tool for your Amiga. It scans a selected directory
for a specified file name or pattern and shows any matching files. You can
then copy, delete, rename or view these matched files.

@{CODE}
Features
  - allows searching by name, comment, size, date, contents or datatype
  - AmigaDOS patterns allowed in search template
  - @{"Indexfiles" link CONCEPT_INDEXFILE} for faster searching
  - even scans through archives (LHa and LZX)
  - allows you to copy, delete, view and rename 
  - configurable Buttons and PopupMenu 
@REM  - easy to use GadTools GUI 
  - shell support 
  - simple ARexx Port
  - and much more
@{BODY}


I know that there are some good tools out there, but some of them use MUI and
others have no GUI at all. I wanted to create one which has an easy to use GUI
and doesn't need MUI (this doesn't mean that I'm +against MUI. MUI is
very powerful and simplifies the development of excellent program interfaces,
for example without MUI some good WWW-Browsers would not exist).

This was for versions earlier than SimpleFind3.
Starting with version 3 SimpleFind uses MUI, too ;-).
The reason is that I have rewritten most of SimpleFind. And it is
of course a lot easier to create a MUI-GUI than a GadTools-GUI.
However I hope to create a GadTools version (maybe with help of
another library), too.


Another reason was that I wanted to test my programming knowledge (this
is my first @{b}real@{ub} program).

@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUIRE "Requirements"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Requirements@{ub}


SimpleFind3 needs at least Kickstart 3.0. It should work with a MC68000
processor but this is not recommended.

SimpleFind3 also need's MUI (at least for this version). I've version
3.8 installed, but no idea if it works with earlier versions.

For using batch files it is also necessary that 'Execute' be located in
the 'C:' assign. But I think that should not be a problem.

SimpleFind3 also supports some packers (LZX, LHa), so if you want to use them
they must be installed (but I imagine that LHa, at least, is installed on
pretty much every Amiga still running [and most of the ones in the closet]).
UnTGZ and UnZip is requiered to support unpacking of TGZ (.tar.zip) and Zip
Archives.


If available, SimpleFind3 will use following libraries/programs, too:


@REM
@REM @{u}ctrequest.library@{uu}@{LINE}
@REM This library is ę1998 by Bahman Moallem. It creates very nice configurable
@REM requesters.
@REM @rem Try it!
@REM
@REM At this time, the library is not available.
@REM
@REM Aminet: util/libs/CTRequest_User.lha
@REM
@REM @{u}popupmenu.library@{uu}@{LINE}
@REM This library is ę1998 by Henrik Isaksson. SimpleFind3 uses this for the Popup-Menus.
@REM
@REM It is avaiable from Aminet, too: util/libs/pmuser.lha
@REM
@REM
@{u}wbstart.library@{uu}@{LINE}
This library is ę1997 by Stefan Becker. You need this library when you
want to start Workbench programs.

Of course it is available from Aminet: util/libs/wbstart.lha


@{u}OpenURL@{uu}@{LINE}
This program is ę1998 by Troels Walsted Hansen. It is used in this guide
to start your favourite browser to see my homepage

Aminet Path: comm/www/OpenURL10.lha


Note that SimpleFind3 doesn't @{b}need@{ub} these files in order to run. They
only provide some additional features.

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "Installation of SimpleFind3"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}How to install SimpleFind3@{ub}


To install SimpleFind3 simply copy the whole SimpleFind3 drawer to the destination of your
choice.

Since version 2.5 there is also an Installation Script available. The advantage
of this script is that you can select another Icon Set which will be installed then
(otherwise you must do this manually). You neither need to remove unnecessary things
(like catalogs) by hand. When installing over an old installation the ToolTypes and
prefs file won't get lost.


@{b}How to remove SimpleFind3@{ub}


If you decide to remove SimpleFind3 (but why would you want to do that???, if you
find any features missing please @{" contact " link SB} me) you should delete
the whole drawer in which the SimpleFind3 program is located.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SHELL "Starting SimpleFind3 from Shell"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Shell Template@{ub}


SimpleFind3 has a standard AmigaDOS template which looks like this:


DIR/M, NAME/K, COM=COMMENT/K, MINSIZE/K, MAXSIZE/K,
WITHIN/K, BETWEEN/K, PROT/K, DATATYPE/K, CONTENTS/K,
EXACT=EXACTNAME/S, EXACTCOM/S, CASENAME/S, CASECOMMENT/S, CASECONTENTS/S,
USEINDEX/S, NOSIZES/S, NODATES/S, LFORMAT/K, GUIMODE/K, PREFSFILE/K


@{u}DIR/M@{uu}@{LINE}
This defines the directories from which to start a search.@{LINE}

@{u}NAME/K@{uu}@{LINE}
A pattern (AmigaDOS-Style) which describes the name.@{LINE}

@{u}COM=COMMENT/K@{uu}@{LINE}
A pattern (AmigaDOS-Style) which describes the comment.@{LINE}

@{u}MINSIZE/K@{uu}@{LINE}
The minimum size. After the integer you can specify the
unit. (m=Mega Bytes; k=Kilo Bytes; b=Bytes (default))@{LINE}
Example: MINSIZE=640 (640 Bytes)@{LINE}

@{u}MAXSIZE/K@{uu}@{LINE}
The maximum size. After the integer you can specify the
unit. (m=Mega Bytes; k=Kilo Bytes; b=Bytes (default))@{LINE}
Example: MAXSIZE=100k (100 Kilo Bytes)@{LINE}

@{u}WITHIN/K@{uu}@{LINE}
Here you specify the maximum desired age of a file to search for. The format is
divided in two parts. The first part is an integer and the second part eighter
MON (Months),D (Days),H (Hours) or MIN (Minutes)@{LINE}
Example: WITHIN=5d@{LINE}

@{u}BETWEEN/K@{uu}@{LINE}
The file must have been created between the specified times.  The format is
"Start-End". The format of the date depends on your selected locale.@{LINE}

@{u}PROT/K@{uu}@{LINE}
Define the protection bits the file have. SimpleFind3 supports the r, w,
e, d, h, s, p, a bits. Using a minus '-' before the bit means that the bit
@{b}must be@{ub} cleared to effect a hit. Bits that don't appear are ignored.@{LINE}

@{u}DATATYPE/K@{uu}@{LINE}
Defines the Datatype Group of the file. To indicate which datatype group the
file should belong to, SimpleFind3 needs one of the standard datatypes.library
strings. Note that this depends on your selected locale!@{LINE}
In the English locale these are: System, Text, Document, Sound, Instrument,
Music, Picture, Animation, Movie.@{LINE}
You also must have the correct datatypes installed (naturally).@{LINE}

@{u}CONTENTS/K@{uu}@{LINE}
With the use of this option you can search through a file for explicit strings.
The lines where the string is found are written in their entirety to the shell
window.@{LINE}

@{u}EXACT=EXACTNAME/S@{uu}@{LINE}
SimpleFind3 doesn't add a #? at the beginning and end of the name-pattern.@{LINE}

@{u}EXACTCOM/S@{uu}@{LINE}
SimpleFind3 doesn't add a #? at the beginning and end of the comment-pattern.@{LINE}

@{u}CASENAME/S@{uu}@{LINE}
Causes SimpleFind3 to ignore the case of the files' name.@{LINE}

@{u}CASECOMMENT/S@{uu}@{LINE}
Causes SimpleFind3 to ignore the case of the files' comment.@{LINE}

@{u}CASECONTENTS/S,@{uu}@{LINE}
Causes SimpleFind3 to ignore the case of the contents@{LINE}

@{u}USEINDEX/S@{uu}@{LINE}
Use the Indexfile for the path, provided that there is an Indexfile.@{LINE}

@{u}NOSIZES/S@{uu}@{LINE}
Don't show size of the files.@{LINE}

@{u}NODATES/S@{uu}@{LINE}
Don't show the date of the files.@{LINE}

@{u}LFORMAT/K@{uu}
@{CODE}
Defines the output format of SimpleFind3.
   %b ....... The file's protection bits
   %c ....... The file's comment
   %d ....... The file's last changed date
   %t ....... The file's last changed time
   %f, %p ... The file's path (with '/')
   %w ....... The file's path (without '/')
   %n ....... The filename
   %l ....... The size (in Bytes) of the file
@{BODY}
To reserve some spaces just add a positive integer after '%'
for right-justification and a negative integer for left-justification.
A period '.' between '%' and the integer
means that the following integer is the limit of the string@{LINE}
Defaults to "%-25n %8l %b %d %t %w"@{LINE}

@{u}GUIMODE/K@{uu}@{LINE}
Gives you control over the GUI Mode of SimpleFind3. The following keywords can be used:
@{CODE}
   NOGUI ........ shell mode (default)
   SHOWGUI ...... opens gui
   QUICKSTART ... opens @{" Main Window " link MAINWND } and starts searching
   FASTERSTART .. starts searching without opening the @{" Main Window " link MAINWND }
@{BODY}
Example: GUIMODE=QUICKSTART@{LINE}

@{u}PREFSFILE/K@{uu}@{LINE}
The name and path of the prefs file which SimpleFind3 will load
upon opening its GUI.@{LINE}
(Defaults to PROGDIR:SimpleFind3.prefs)

@ENDNODE

@NODE WB "Starting SimpleFind3 from Workbench"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Workbench Start@{ub}

SimpleFind3 can be started from Workbench by double clicking the SimpleFind3-icon.

SimpleFind3 also supports multiselection, so if you first click on
SimpleFind3's Icon and then shiftclick on a Partition or Drawer it
will use this as the starting Search Path.


@{b}Tool Types@{ub}@{LINE}
Currently there are two ToolTypes.@{LINE}

@{u}PREFSFILE@{uu}@{LINE}
Here you can specify the path and the name of the prefs file which is created
when you select @{" SaveSettings as Default" link MENU} in the @{" menu " link MENU}
and which is loaded at the start of SimpleFind3.@{LINE}
(Defaults to PROGDIR:SimpleFind3.prefs)@{LINE}

@{u}IMAGE@{uu}@{LINE}
Path to an image to be displayed in the @{" Main Window " link MAINWND}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GUI "The User Interface"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}The User Interface@{ub}


SimpleFind3's user interface essentially consists of four windows. All windows
use the same @{" Menu " link MENU}.

If you start SimpleFind3 normally, it first opens the
@{" Main Window " link MAINWND}.  Within this window you have full control over
SimpleFind3's search capabilities and it is here where you start the Search Process.

When you press the "Start Search" button in the bottom of the window the
@{" Result Window " link RESULTWND} appears. The @{"Search Process" link CONCEPT_SEARCHPROCESS}
starts now and the files which match the options are displayed.
You can select these files and manipulate them (for example you can copy, rename or delete them).
The buttons you see in the window can be freely configured.@{LINES}

If you select the "Windows/Index Manager..." entry from the
@{"Menu" link MENU}, the @{"Indexmanager Window" link IMANWND} will appear.
It is here that you create, delete or update
@{"Indexfiles" link CONCEPT_INDEXFILE}.@{LINE}

Settings are altered in the @{" Setttings Window " link SETTWND} which appears
after selecting the menu entry "Settings/Configuration...".

Every search group also has it's own settings. These can be changed in the
@{"Group Settings Window " link GROUPSETTWND}.

@{CODE}
Windows:
@{" Main Window           " link MAINWND }  Control Searching
@{" Result Window         " link RESULTWND }  Shows matching files
@{" IndexManager Window   " link IMANWND }  Manage your Indexfiles
@{" Settings Window       " link SETTWND}  Alter SF3's Settings
@{" Group Settings Window " link GROUPSETTWND}  Change the settings of a group

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU "SimpleFind3's Menu"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Menu@{ub}


SimpleFind3's menus are reachable from nearly every window. With the menus you
control important functions of SimpleFind3.


SimpleFind3 provides the following menu items:

@{" Project  " link MENU_PROJECT}   Information@{LINE}
@{" Group    " link MENU_OPTIONS}   Local Options@{LINE}
@{" Windows  " link MENU_WINDOWS}   Windows of SimpleFind3@{LINE}
@{" Settings " link MENU_SETTINGS}   Global Settings@{LINE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_PROJECT "Menu: Project"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 25
@{b}Project Menu@{ub}@{LINE}

The Project Menu consists of four items:@{LINE}

@{b}About...@{ub}@{LINDENT 25}@{TAB}
Shows information about the copyright, the author (hey, that's me :-) ),
and the language creator.
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}About MUI...@{ub}@{LINDENT 25}@{TAB}
Shows information about MUI.
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}Execute ARexx Script...@{ub}@{LINDENT 25}@{TAB}
Popups an asl requester from which you can choose a Arexx Script to be executed
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}Quit@{ub}@{LINDENT 25}@{TAB}
Quits SimpleFind3 without notifing the user.
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_USEINDEX "Menuitem: Use Indexfiles?"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Use Indexfiles?@{ub}@{LINE}

If checked SimpleFind3 uses the indexfile for the particular search path,
provided that such an Indexfile exists.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_DONTSB "Menuitem: Don't save Between?"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Don't save Between?@{ub}@{LINE}

If checked SimpleFind3 doesn't save the contents of the Between Search
Option (ehich is the same as the old SimpleFind did)

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_GROUPSETT "Menuitem: Group Settings..."
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Group Settings...@{ub}@{LINE}

Opens the @{" Group Settings " link GROUPSETTWND} for the selected search group.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_NAME "Submenu: Name"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 16
@{b}Name Submenu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can influence some option concerning the files' name. Following options
are available:@{LINE}

@{b}Case sensitive?@{ub}@{LINDENT 16}@{TAB}
If checked SimpleFind3 recognizes the filenames' case.
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}Exact?@{ub}@{LINDENT 16}@{TAB}
If selected SimpleFind3 doesn't add the '#?' surrounding the name-pattern.
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_COMMENT "Submenu: Comment"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 16
@{b}Comment Submenu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can influence some option concerning the files' comment.
The following options are available:@{LINE}

@{b}Case sensitive?@{ub}@{LINDENT 16}@{TAB}
If checked SimpleFind3 recognizes the comments' case.
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}Exact?@{ub}@{LINDENT 16}@{TAB}
If selected SimpleFind3 doesn't add the '#?' surrounding the comment pattern
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_CONTENTS "Submenu: Contents"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 19
@{b}Contents Submenu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can set some options influencing the contents search.
The following options are available:@{LINE}

@{b}Case sensitive?@{ub}@{LINDENT 19}@{TAB}
If not checked SimpleFind3 irgnore the case of the contents
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}Force string mode?@{ub}@{LINDENT 19}@{TAB}
If checked the @{" String Mode " link CONCEPT_STRINGMODE} is forced.
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPT_SEARCHFOR "Submenu: Search for"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 24
@{b}Search for Submenu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can define which types (files or directories) should be
listed.@{LINE}

@{b}Files@{ub}@{LINDENT 24}@{TAB}
Search for files only.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}Drawers@{ub}@{LINDENT 24}@{TAB}
Search for drawers only.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}Files and Drawers@{ub}@{LINDENT 24}@{TAB}
Search for files and drawers.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}Inside Archives?@{ub}@{LINDENT 22}@{TAB}
Look for files in Archives (Lha/LZX), too?
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_OPTIONS "Menu: Group"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 27
@{b}Options Menu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can change the behaviour of some search options within the selected group.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

@{b}@{"  Use Indexfiles?       " link MENU_OPT_USEINDEX}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Use the indexfiles.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}@{"  Don't save Between?   " link MENU_OPT_DONTSB}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Don't save the between contents.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}@{" Name                 ╗ " link MENU_OPT_NAME}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Some options to influence the name search option.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}@{" Comment              ╗ " link MENU_OPT_COMMENT}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Some options to influence the comment search option.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}@{" Contents             ╗ " link MENU_OPT_CONTENTS}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Some options to influence the contents search option.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}@{" Search for           ╗ " link MENU_OPT_SEARCHFOR}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
For which types SimpleFind3 should search for.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}@{" Group Settings...      " link MENU_OPT_GROUPSETT}@{ub}@{LINDENT 27}@{TAB}
Change the Group Settings.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}


@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_WINDOWS "Menu: Windows"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Windows Menu@{ub}@{LINE}

Open/Activate SimpleFind3's Windows.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETTINGS "Menu: Settings"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 26
@{b}Settings Menu@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can alter SimpleFind3's settings:@{LINE}
@{b}Quick Search Start?@{ub}@{LINDENT 24}@{TAB}
Search after a name pattern has been entered?
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}Configuration...@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Opens the @{" Settings Window " link SETTWND}.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}MUI...@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Opens the MUI Configuration.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}Load Settings...@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Loads the selected settings into SimpleFind3.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}Save Settings@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Saves the settings to the last loaded location.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}Save Settings As...@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Save the settings to a selected path.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{b}Save Settings As Default@{ub}@{LINDENT 26}@{TAB}
Saves the settings to the default path.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND "Main Window"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 18
@{b}Main Window@{ub}@{LINE}

The Main Window is opened shortly after starting.
Within this window you can specify the
criteria for a @{" Search Process " link CONCEPT_SEARCHPROCESS}.

It is mainly divided into three sections. On the left you can
manage all the search groups. On the right you can specify them
and with the button on the bottom the @{" Search Process " link CONCEPT_SEARCHPROCESS} can
be started.


@{b}Searchgroup-List@{ub}@{LINE}
Here you can manage the Searchgroups. You can create a new group, rename a group
or delete the selected group. Every group has its own settings too. Doubleclick on
an entry brings up the @{" Group Settings Window " link GROUPSETTWND} for this entry.


@{b}The 'Search Options' group@{ub}@{LINE}
This is the group where you specify the single criteria for the search group. These criteria
are used for the @{" Search Process " link CONCEPT_SEARCHPROCESS}@{LINE}

@{" Search Path   " link MAINWND_SEARCHPATH}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Through which paths SF3 should search
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Max. Dir Deep " link MAINWND_DIRDEEP}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Maximum depth of directories through which SimpleFind3 searches.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Name          " link MAINWND_NAME}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search for file names.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Comment       " link MAINWND_COMMENT}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search for file comments.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Min Size      " link MAINWND_MINSIZE}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Minimum file size.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Max Size      " link MAINWND_MAXSIZE}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Maximum file size.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Within last   " link MAINWND_WITHINLAST}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search only for objects created since a particular date.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Between       " link MAINWND_BETWEEN}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search only for objects created between two points in time.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Prot. Bits    " link MAINWND_PROTBITS}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search for Protection Bits.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Datatype      " link MAINWND_DATATYPE}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search for a datatype.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Contents      " link MAINWND_CONTENTS}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Search for a string in a file.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Compare       " link MAINWND_COMPARE}@{LINDENT 18}@{TAB}Compare every file with each other.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@{b}The 'Start Search...' Button@{ub}@{LINE}
When you are finished with the search options you press the
@{" Start Search... " link MAINWND_STARTSEARCH} button.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_SEARCHPATH "Main Window: Search Path"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Search Path@{ub}@{LINE}

This is the path where SimpleFind3 will start its search. There
are three posibilities to enter the path:


░ @{LINDENT 2}
You can enter this path manually within the string gadget.
Multiple paths are separated by '|'.
@{LINDENT 0}

░ @{LINDENT 2}
You can click onto the file requester button to the right of the string gadget
which brings up a filerequester. This filerequester can also be brought up by pressing
the <Shift>-Key together with the underscored sign of the gadgettext
(in english language this would be <Shift>+<p>).
@{LINDENT 0}

░ @{LINDENT 2}
You can click on the rightmost button which makes the path manager
appear. Currently this consits only of a multiselectable
listview which shows all available and mounted devices. Doubleclicking
an entry or pressing Ok will close the window and set the new search
path.
@{LINDENT 0}


Staring with version 1.2 of SimpleFind3 the search path can also consits of AmigaOS
patterns. Then a internal list of all possible paths which matches the path is built
when the search process starts. Note that when you use the '|' AmigaOS pattern sign
you must enclose the path in quotation marks (").

Some path examples:@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

 SYS:S
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
only searches in SYS:S@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

 SYS:S|SYS:C
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
searches in SYS:S and in SYS:C@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

 SYS:S#?
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
searches in every directory in SYS: which name starts with S@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

 "SYS:C#?/(data#?|#?gets)"|SYS:L
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
looks in every directory in SYS: which starts with C if there are
directories which starts with "data" or ends with "gets" and searches
in them and in SYS:L@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 0}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_NAME "Main Window: Name"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Name@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the files' names with
the AmigaOS pattern given in the string gadget. If a name matches
the pattern it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_COMMENT "Main Window: Comment"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Comment@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the files' comments with
the AmigaOS pattern given in the string gadget. If a comment matches
the pattern it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_MINSIZE "Main Window: Min Size"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Min Size@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the size of the file with
the given number. If the file's size is greater or equals the number
it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE


@NODE MAINWND_MAXSIZE "Main Window: Max Size"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Max Size@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the size of the file with
the given number. If the file's size is less or equals the number
it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_WITHINLAST "Main Window: Within last"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Within last@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the creation date of the
file with the given number. If the creation date is within the timespan
which has been entered it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_BETWEEN "Main Window: Between"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Between@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares the creation date of the
file with the two given dates. If the creation date is between (or equals)
the given dates it will be interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_PROTBITS "Main Window: Protection Bits"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Protection Bits@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 checks for the protection bit of the
file. If the file's protection bits matches the given string it
will be interpreted an a hit.@{LINE}
The following bits are supported:  r, w, e, d, h, s, p, a.
Within the string, a minus '-' before the bit means "not set", otherwise "set".
Bits which don't appear are ignored. By clicking on to the button next
to the string gadget a new window will open, in which you can choose the
bits with the mouse.@{LINE}

@{u}Example@{uu}@{LINE}
Protection Bits: -ar@{LINE}
All files which have the a bit not set and the r bit set are
interpreted as a hit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_DATATYPE "Main Window: Datatype"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Datatype@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated the file must belong to a selected datatype group
to be interpreted as a hit.@{LINE}
Click on the button to show all possible groups. Note that the datatypes.library
is used, so be sure to have the correct datatype installed.@{LINE}
Also note that actually this option doesn't work for files inside archives.

@ENDNODE


@NODE MAINWND_CONTENTS "Main Window: Contents"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Contents@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 scans through the entire file, searching for the specified string.
If it found at least one string inside this file, it will be interpreted as a hit.@{LINE}
The strings which where found inside the file are then displayed in a seperate window which
is opened as soon you click onto a entry inside the @{" Result Window " link RESULTWND}.@{LINE}
Note that this option can slow down the search process dramatically if you don't specify any other
option.@{LINE}
Also note that actually this option doesn't work for files inside archives.

@ENDNODE


@NODE MAINWND_COMPARE "Main Window: Compare"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Compare@{ub}@{LINE}

If this option is activated SimpleFind3 compares every found file with each other.
If two files matches each other (depending on the given compare mode), both files
are interpreted as a hit.@{LINE}
Note that the compare option can slow down the search process dramatically.@{LINE}

@{b}Available compare modes@{ub}@{LINE}
1) Filenames only@{LINE}
Only the filename of the files are compared. This mode is slow.@{LINE}

2) Filenames and sizes - the filenames and the sizes of the files are compared@{LINE}
The filenames and the sizes are compared. This is the fastest mode.@{LINE}

3) Filenames and contents@{LINE}
The filenames and the whole contents are compared. This mode is slow.@{LINE}

4) Contents
The contents of each file is compared. This mode is @{b}very@{ub} slow.@{LINE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_DIRDEEP "Main Window: Max Dir Deep"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Max. Directory@{ub}@{LINE}

This defines the maximum depth of directories to be scanned by SimpleFind3.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINWND_STARTSEARCH "Main Window: Start Search"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Start Search@{ub}@{LINE}

This will start the @{" Search Process " link CONCEPT_SEARCHPROCESS}. The results
are shown in the @{" Result Window " link RESULTWND }. During a search, breaking
is possible with 'Esc' or clicking on the Results Closegadget.

@ENDNODE

@NODE RESULTWND "Result Window"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Result Window@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you see a listview which shows the found files soon after they are found.@{LINE}
Clicking on an entry will select a file. The number of selected files is displayed
in the textgadget below the listview.@{LINE}

The buttons that you will find here are configurable (see the
@{" Settings " link SETTWND} / @{" Buttons " link SETTWND_BUTTONS} section).

If desired/required there is also a popup menu available which is freely
configurable as well (see the
@{" Settings " link SETTWND} / @{" Popup Menu " link SETTWND_POPUP} section).
The menu is shown if you press the right mouse button over the listview.@{LINE}

If you use the default preferences you will find the following buttons:@{LINE}
@{" Information " link ICMD_INFO}  Workbench Information Requester@{LINE}
@{" Copy        " link ICMD_COPY}  Copy selected files@{LINE}
@{" Delete      " link ICMD_DELETE}  Delete selected files@{LINE}
@{" Show        " link ICMD_SHOW}  Show selected files@{LINE}
@{" Archive     " link ICMD_ARCHIVE}  Archive selected files@{LINE}
@{" Unpack      " link ICMD_UNPACK}  Unpack selected files@{LINE}

@ENDNODE


@NODE IMANWND "Indexmanager Window"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}IndexManager Window@{ub}


It is here where you manage your @{"Indexfiles" link CONCEPT_INDEXFILE}. This means
you can create new indexfiles and update or delete old ones.@{LINE}

Available indexfiles are shown in the @{" Listview " link IMANWND_AVAIL} Gadget.@{LINE}

You will find the following other gadgets in this window:@{LINE}
@{" Create... " link IMANWND_CREATE}  Create a new Indexfile@{LINE}
@{" Update    " link IMANWND_UPDATE}  Update the current Indexfile@{LINE}
@{" Delete    " link IMANWND_DELETE}  Delete the current Indexfile@{LINE}

@ENDNODE

@NODE IMANWND_AVAIL "Indexmanager Window: Available Indexfiles Listview"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Available Indexfiles Listview@{ub}


The listview shows the available indexfiles. You will see for which partition
or drawer an indexfile has been created and when it was last updated.
To select an entry click on the left mouse button over the entry or use
the cursor keys. Performing a double click over an entry or pressing enter
will change the @{" Search Path " link MAINWND_SEARCHPATH} in the @{" Main Window " link MAINWND}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE IMANWND_CREATE "Indexmanager Window: Create Indexfile"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Create@{ub}


Press this button to create an new indexfile. In the filerequester you
choose the wanted drawer or partition.

@ENDNODE


@NODE IMANWND_UPDATE "Indexmanager Window: Update Indexfile"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Update@{ub}


Press this button to update the selected indexfile.

@ENDNODE


@NODE IMANWND_DELETE "Indexmanager Window: Delete Indexfile"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Delete@{ub}


Press this button to delete the selected indexfile.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SETTWND "Settings Window"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 15
@{b}Settings Window@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can configure important aspects of SimpleFind3 to
your particular needs.@{LINE}
At the top you can see all available pages. Clicking onto a name will
switch to this page.
The actual page is visible in the big middle part of the window.
On the bottom part there are two gadgets: Ok and Cancel. Ok accepts
the settings and cancel rejects them.@{LINE}

Pages:@{LINE}
@{" General    " link SETTWND_GENERAL}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Useful things.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Buttons    " link SETTWND_BUTTONS}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Configure the buttons in the Result Window.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Popup Menu " link SETTWND_POPUP}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Configure the popupmenus.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Extra Menu " link SETTWND_EXTRA}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Configure the extra menu.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE


@NODE SETTWND_GENERAL "Settings Page: General"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}General Settings@{ub}@{LINE}

@{u}Options File@{uu}@{LINE}
The filename where the options are located.@{LINE}

@{u}Indexfile Directory@{uu}@{LINE}
The directory where all Indexfiles are saved.@{LINE}

@{u}Unpack Directoty@{uu}@{LINE}
The default unpack directoty.@{LINE}

@{u}ARexx Script Directory@{uu}@{LINE}
The default initial directory of the ARexx Script File Requester@{LINE}

@{u}Archiver@{uu}@{LINE}
The archiver used to pack files.@{LINE}

@{u}Double Click@{uu}@{LINE}
Performs this @{" Action " link CONCEPT_ACTION} when double clicking inside the Result Window.@{LINE}

@ENDNODE


@NODE SETTWND_BUTTONS "Settings Page: Buttons"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Buttons@{ub}


Here you can configure the buttons that are shown in the 
@{" Result Window " link RESULTWND}.  The page consists of one listview, two
string gadgets, one cycle gadget and several buttons.

In the listview we see all the names of currently available buttons. Every
entry represents a button except a line, which is a separator between button
groups. In the @{" Result Window " link RESULTWND} we see different groups in
different lines.

Below the the listview there is a string gadget where you can change the label of
the button which is selected. In the label, the mark or sign behind behind the underscore (_)
represents the short cut for the button.

Below this button is another string gadget. Here you enter the @{" Action " link CONCEPT_ACTION} which is
performed when pressing the button.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SETTWND_POPUP "Preferences Page: Popup Menu"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Popup Menu@{ub}


This page is similar to the @{" Buttons " link SETTWND_BUTTONS} Page, but instead
of creating buttons you create popup menu entries. Also, groups don't actually 
exist, but you can still create separators.

The popup menu is shown if you press the right mouse button over the
@{" Result Window " link RESULTWND} and if the popupmenu.library has been opened.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SETTWND_EXTRA "Preferences Page: Extra Menu"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Extra Menu@{ub}@{LINE}

This page is similar to the @{" Buttons " link SETTWND_BUTTONS} Page, but instead
of creating buttons you create menu entries in the Extra Menu. Also, groups don't actually 
exist, but you can still create separators.

@ENDNODE


@NODE GROUPSETTWND_OUTPUTFMT "Group Settings Page: Output Format"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Output@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can easily change the output format of
the files which are shown in the @{" Result Window " link RESULTWND}.

In case the output should be the same as the default group simply
activate the "As Default" checkbox.

Inside the listview there are all available Output elements.
If you select one of them you can change the position,
the justification (via the cycle gadget) and whether it should be activated
(via double click on the column's name). Deactivated entries are surrounded
by brackets.

@ENDNODE


@NODE GROUPSETTWND "Group Settings Window"
@SMARTWRAP
@TAB 14
@{b}Group Settings Window@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can edit some group dependent settings. On the top
of the window you can see the name of the group for which
the settings are. As you can see the different settings are
grouped in several pages. Pressing on the Ok button will accept
the change while Cancel will reject the change.@{LINE}

Pages:@{LINE}
@{" Visibilty " link GROUPSETTWND_VISIBILTY}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Visiblity of the search options.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Scripts   " link GROUPSETTWND_SCRIPTS}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}ARexx Scripts
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@{" Output    " link GROUPSETTWND_OUTPUTFMT}
@{LINDENT 15}@{TAB}Configure the output format used in the Result Window.
@{LINDENT 0}@{LINE}
@ENDNODE

@NODE GROUPSETTWND_VISIBILTY "Group Settings Page: Visibility"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Visibility@{ub}@{LINE}

In the listview you can choose which options are visible when this
group is selected. Doubleclicking on an entry change the visibility
from "As Default" to "Unvisible" to "Visible". "As Default" is not
available for the default group. It means that the visiblility
is like the default group.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GROUPSETTWND_SCRIPTS "Group Settings Page: Scripts"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Scripts@{ub}@{LINE}

Here you can link an ARexx Script with a event. All available
events are displayed in the listview. By Doubleclicking on
an entry you change the state from "As Default" to "Disabled"
to "Enabled". The script which will be used can be defined
inside the string gadget below the listview. Next to the
string gadget there is a checkbox "Sync". Here you can choose
whether the script should be runned synchron (SF3 waits until
the script finished) or asynchron.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FUTURE "Future"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Future@{ub}
@{CODE}

I plan to add the following features:

  - ReAction GUI which is coming with OS3.5
  - implement the rest which is missing from version 2.5
    (auto-updating, arexx notification)
  - maybe gadtools version
  - any other suggestions if I think they are any good
    (for example I will @{b}not@{ub} add a racing game
    or a function plotter ;-) )
@{BODY}

The first point has the highest priority (and of course your suggestions,
there are still a lot left ;-) ).


But what I don't want to add is direct filetypes support, because you have this
already (indirectly). Simply choose a filetype-identification tool as
SimpleFind3's Viewer. There are lots of them on Aminet and this method works well
for me.

@ENDNODE

@NODE BUGS "Known Bugs"
@SMARTWRAP
@{b}Problem 1@{ub}

Some people again reported problems with Indexfile-Updating.


@{b}My Explanation@{ub}

Indexfile Updating still not perfect :-(
(Has been rewritten for SF3 which should solve the problem)

Another reason is that the OS doesn't update the file's date
when changing only the comment.


@{b}Solution@{ub}

If the cause revolves around file comments I cannot fix it :-(

Otherwise you would help me a lot if you could send me the updated (corrupt)
and original Indexfiles. But please only Lha or LZx packed and not huge
ones (the e-Mail shouldn't be > 250KB).



@{b}Problem 2@{ub}

The Information Button doesn't work in conjunction with DOpus (WB replacement).
(reported by Manfred Ambros)


@{b}My Explanation@{ub}

The Workbench function SimpleFind3 calls requires a previously loaded Workbench.
When you use DOpus as a WB-Replacement the original Workbench isn't loaded
and the call fails.


@{b}Solution@{ub}

Using an InfoRequester Patcher should solve the problem.

I've also heard that newer versions of DOpus(>= 5.66) have an option which
solves that problem.

There's a Env Variable called " PatchWBInfo ". You must create it an set it
to "1", and must be placed in Env:Dopus .

You also can use the program "DO5ExtPrefs", by Jens Weyer (actually v1.6)

@REM @{b}Problem 3@{ub}
@REM 
@REM When using the ARexx Script for DOpus the found files can't be copied from
@REM one listview to another.
@REM 
@REM 
@REM @{b}My Explanation@{ub}
@REM 
@REM DOpus doesn't handle Fullpath names correctly.
@REM 
@REM 
@REM @{b}Solution@{ub}
@REM 
@REM Not known to exist at this time. If somebody has a solution,
@REM contact @{" me " link SB}.


@ENDNODE

